    <article>
      <h2 class="site-article-headline hca-typography--headline">When creating navigation</h2>
      <section class="site-section">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-12">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Take inventory</h3>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Identify your app’s and website’s users and their potential roles, such as patient, visitor, business owner, or physician. Identify the most common tasks they may want to perform.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Prioritize</h3>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Assign priority levels of high, medium, or low to common user tasks. Give prominence in the UI to paths and destinations with high priority levels and frequent use.</p>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Adjust priority levels as user needs change over time.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Sequence</h3>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Identify the different paths that users take through your app or website and use those paths to define your navigation. People should always know where they are in your app and how to get to their next destination. Regardless of navigation style, it’s essential that the path through content is logical, predictable, and easy to follow. In general on mobile, give people one path to each screen.</p>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">List frequent destinations prominently in your navigation</p>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Group related tasks together and use those groupings to structure your navigation</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr />

      <section class="site-section">
        <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Navigational Menu Icon</h3>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-5">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Utilize a triple stack (hamburger) menu icon when condensing your navigation. A menu icon should always be accompanied with the text “Menu” below or beside. The menu icon will exist on the top left of your website and is not adjacent to any other icon.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2">
            <figure class="hca-visual-example">
              <img src="{{page.base_url}}images/patterns/navigation/menu-icon.png" class="img-responsive hca-visual-example__comp" alt="" />
              {{!-- <figcaption class="hca-visual-example__caption hca-typography--caption"></figcaption> --}}
            </figure>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="site-section">
        <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Full Page Navigation (Small Screens)</h3>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-5">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Full page navigation allows for the most space to support complex navigation structures on mobile. Full page navigation will cover the view of the entire website so the user is focused on navigation. Full page navigations will be accompanied with the word “close” in the top left where the menu icon once was on the screen. When there are multiple levels of navigation you may nest options beneath a parent utilizing the expansion panel rules. Full page navigation can also include a search bar and a bottom navigation bar.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-sm-7">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-sm-6">
