      <section class="site-section">
        <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Trees</h3>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-5">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Organize pages in a tree to indicate hierarchy. Use a tree if your app has layered navigation that can’t be represented in a simple tab set. A tree helps users navigate to pages and quickly find a nested child page without loading each page while navigating to the final destination page. Be sure to carefully study the mental models of users when deciding how to group pages in your tree.</p>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">You can use a tree in conjunction with breadcrumbs to further help users navigate the hierarchy.</p>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Trees can technically have unlimited nesting, but we recommend avoiding excessive nesting. Flatter trees are generally easier to navigate. Every item in the list doesn’t have to have a corresponding page. Instead, you can use label groups to organize related pages without providing an unnecessary landing page.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2">
            <figure class="hca-visual-example">
              <img src="{{page.base_url}}images/patterns/navigation/trees.png" class="img-responsive hca-visual-example__comp" alt="" />
              {{!-- <figcaption class="hca-visual-example__caption hca-typography--caption"></figcaption> --}}
            </figure>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="site-section">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-12">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Hover, Action, and Focus States</h3>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">Items in navigation should have different actionable states to assist those who navigate websites with their keyboard. These states should be easily identifiable to those with visual impairments. Do not solely distinguish action states with color.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Menu List Ordering</h3>
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">It is best practice to prioritize highly frequented locations of your site in the navigation. Ordering dropdowns by popularity opposed to alphabetical order provides users a more relatable experience.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="site-section">
        <h3 class="hca-typography--title">Adaptive Navigation</h3>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-sm-5">
            <div class="site-container--body-content">
              <p class="hca-typography--body-1">On some mobile experiences, your navigation structure may lend itself to be adapted opposed to responsive. If this is the case, try prioritizing the most critical information while the rest may be hidden under a few layers of navigation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2">
